Tom,<br><br>
Ours is a difference of point of view rather than substance. It seems every 'Nam Vet has his/her own personal reaction and view on what went on. What we all seem to agree upon was that it was just plain wrong, bad, awful, wicked sucky, and all the rest of it, and many 'Nam Vets never broke even psychologically or physically, as we know.<br><br>
Can I forget the wrong things that went on?<br><br>
No.<br><br>
Can I say that those wrong things are forgiven or OK?<br><br>
No.<br><br>
Can I understand why some of those wrong things happened?<br><br>
I am trying. I think have some understanding as I go back in time and explore my own feelings on these issues.<br><br>
Can I judge those who did wrong things more harshly than others outside of this experience who have done the same kinds of wrong things?<br><br>
No.<br><br>
Have I really figured out just exactly what I consider wrong?<br><br>
That's the question!<br><br>
Now, that may sound a little wierd to some people, but considering the balancing act going on in my head, I am not entirely sure where some of the shades of gray are going to land.<br><br>
We must not loose sight of the fact that it *was* war, life in the extreme, life beyond the extreme, life pushed to the edge of simple survival, the &quot;rules&quot; of society and conduct evaporating befor the raw fear of imminent death.<br><br>
How can you judge some of this stuff?<br><br>
That's where I'm at. The great debate, the balancing act, and my answers still lie within.<br><br>
  
